{:proof/problem-id "apm-a98A06", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK ‚ÄĒ mentions-problem-objects? ‚úÖ (analytic \\(f\\) on \\( \\mathbf C\\setminus\\{0\\}\\), bounded \\( |f(z)||z|^{1/2}\\), removable singularity at \\(0\\)) ¬∑ avoids-assuming-conclusion? ‚úÖ (the Lean target asserts the existence of a holomorphic extension without presuming it) ¬∑ meaningful-without-prose? ‚úÖ (states a precise removable-singularity theorem) ¬∑ notes: helper lemma is the classical Riemann removable singularity theorem used on \\(zf\\).\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Prove that an analytic f on (‚Ąā \\\\ {0}) with |f(z)||z|^{1/2} locally bounded has a removable singularity at 0.\"\n :terms [{:name \"bounded product\"\n          :meaning \"The hypothesis says g(z)=z^{1/2}f(z) is bounded near 0.\"\n          :needed-because \"Bounded holomorphic functions on punctured discs extend holomorphically.\"}\n         {:name \"Riemann removable singularity theorem\"\n          :meaning \"If a holomorphic function on a punctured disc is bounded, it extends holomorphically across the puncture.\"\n          :needed-because \"Allows us to extend zf through 0 once we show it tends to 0.\"}\n         {:name \"zero factoring\"\n          :meaning \"Analytic g with g(0)=0 factors as g(z)=z h(z) with h analytic.\"\n          :needed-because \"After extending zf, dividing out by z yields an analytic extension for f.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Removable singularity theorem\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 estimate |zf(z)| ‚Č§ C|z|^{1/2}\"\n             :why-this-now \"Show zf is bounded near 0, so it extends holomorphically with value 0.\"\n             :lean-target \"extend_z_mul_f\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already contains Riemann's removable theorem.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Factorization of zeros / analytic division\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 final step\"\n             :why-this-now \"Use the extension of zf and the zero at 0 to define an analytic h with f=h, proving removability.\"\n             :lean-target \"analyticExtension_from_zero_factor\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib has `IsROrC` results on factoring zeros.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"A holomorphic f on (‚Ąā‚ąĖ{0}) with |f(z)||z|^{1/2} locally bounded extends holomorphically across 0.\"\n             :formal-name \"removable_singularity_half_power\"\n             :formal-target \"‚ąÄ {U : Set ‚Ąā} (hU : IsOpen U) (h0 : (0 : ‚Ąā) ‚ąą U)\n  {f : ‚Ąā ‚Üí ‚Ąā}, HolomorphicOn f (U \\\\ {0}) ‚Üí\n  (‚ąÉ C > 0, ‚ąÄ z ‚ąą U \\\\ {0}, ‚ÄĖf z‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖz‚ÄĖ ^ (2‚ĀĽ¬Ļ : ‚ĄĚ) ‚Č§ C) ‚Üí\n  ‚ąÉ g : ‚Ąā ‚Üí ‚Ąā, HolomorphicOn g U ‚ąß EqOn g f (U \\\\ {0}).\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Encodes the analytic extension statement the problem asks for.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"removable_singularity_half_power\"\n              :formal-statement \"same as formal-target\"\n              :informal-clause \"Certifies that f has a removable singularity at 0.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"riemann_removable\"\n              :formal-statement \"Bounded holomorphic functions on a punctured disc extend holomorphically across the puncture.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Used to extend zf through 0 before dividing by z.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK ‚ÄĒ mentions-problem-objects? ‚úÖ (analytic \\(f\\) on \\(C\\setminus\\{0\\}\\), the weighted bound \\(|f(z)||z|^{1/2}\\), and the removable-singularity conclusion all appear explicitly) ¬∑ avoids-assuming-conclusion? ‚úÖ (the Lean target concludes the existence of a holomorphic extension rather than assuming it) ¬∑ meaningful-without-prose? ‚úÖ (it is a standalone removable-singularity theorem tied to the stated bound) ¬∑ notes: Plan + alignment now reference boundedness of \\(z f(z)\\), Riemann‚Äôs removable theorem, and analytic division, matching both the informal proof and the Lean strategy.\n\n```clojure\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that an analytic f on C\\\\{0} whose weighted modulus |f(z)||z|^{1/2} stays bounded near 0 extends holomorphically across 0.\"\n :terms [{:name \"bounded product\"\n          :meaning \"From |f(z)||z|^{1/2} <= C on a punctured disc we get |z f(z)| <= C r^{1/2} for |z|<r.\"\n          :needed-because \"Producing a bounded holomorphic function on the punctured disc lets us invoke Riemann's removable theorem.\"}\n         {:name \"Riemann removable singularity theorem\"\n          :meaning \"Any holomorphic function on a punctured disc that is bounded extends holomorphically over the centre.\"\n          :needed-because \"Apply it to g(z)=z f(z) to build an analytic extension G with G(0)=0.\"}\n         {:name \"zero factoring / analytic division\"\n          :meaning \"If G is analytic and G(0)=0 then G(z)=z*H(z) with H analytic.\"\n          :needed-because \"Defining H(0)=G'(0) yields the desired extension of f.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"riemannRemovable\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Bound g(z)=z f(z) on a small punctured neighbourhood\"\n             :why-this-now \"Once g is bounded, the removable-singularity theorem gives an analytic G with G=z f on punctured disc.\"\n             :lean-target \"extend_z_mul_f\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Available in Mathlib as `IsHolomorphic.bounded_implies_removable`. \"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"analytic_division_by_z\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Output of :s1 (extension for zf with zero at 0)\"\n             :why-this-now \"Factor the zero to define H so that H=z^{-1}G agrees with f away from 0, showing f extends analytically.\"\n             :lean-target \"extend_f_via_factor\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib supports factoring zeros through `HasFPowerSeriesAt`. \"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```clojure\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Any analytic f on C\\\\{0} whose product |f(z)||z|^{1/2} stays bounded near 0 extends holomorphically across 0.\"\n             :formal-name \"removableSingularity_halfPower\"\n             :formal-target \"Given an open set U : Set Complex with 0 in U and a function f : Complex -> Complex that is holomorphic on U \\\\ {0}, if there exists C > 0 such that Complex.abs (f z) * Complex.abs z ^ ((1 : Real) / 2) <= C for every z in U \\\\ {0}, then there exists g : Complex -> Complex that is holomorphic on U and agrees with f on U \\\\ {0}.\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Exactly encodes the claim ‚Äúf has a removable singularity at 0 under the stated bound.‚ÄĚ\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"removableSingularity_halfPower\"\n              :formal-statement \"same as formal-target\"\n              :informal-clause \"Stage 1 conclusion that f extends over 0.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"riemannRemovable\"\n              :formal-statement \"For any open set U : Set Complex and any holomorphic f : Complex -> Complex on U \\\\ {0} that is bounded on that punctured set, there exists g holomorphic on U that equals f on U \\\\ {0}.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Justifies extending g(z)=z f(z) once it is bounded.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it‚Äôs hard.**  The hypothesis controls only the weighted product \\(|f(z)|\\,|z|^{1/2}\\) near the puncture, whereas the usual removable-singularity criterion wants \\(|f|\\) itself to be bounded. Trying to quote Riemann‚Äôs theorem on \\(f\\) therefore stalls: the weight goes to infinity instead of zero, so the naive bound cannot hold. The fix is to modify \\(f\\) in a way that absorbs the dangerous factor of \\(|z|^{-1/2}\\) and produces an honestly bounded holomorphic function.\n\n**Key insight.**  Look at \\(g(z)=z\\,f(z)\\). On a small disc \\(|z|\\le r\\) we still have \\(|f(z)||z|^{1/2}\\le C\\), so\n\\[\n|g(z)|=|z|\\cdot |f(z)|=\\bigl(|f(z)||z|^{1/2}\\bigr)\\,|z|^{1/2}\\le C\\,r^{1/2}.\n\\]\nThus \\(g\\) is bounded and holomorphic on the punctured disc, so Riemann‚Äôs theorem extends \\(g\\) holomorphically across \\(0\\). Because the weighted bound forces \\(g(z)\\to 0\\), the extension vanishes at the origin, and dividing by \\(z\\) (implemented as Mathlib‚Äôs `dslope`) finishes the job.\n\n**Complete proof.**  \nPick an open neighbourhood \\(N\\) of \\(0\\) on which \\(|f(z)|\\,|z|^{1/2}\\le C\\). Shrink if necessary so that the closed disc \\(\\overline{B}(0,r)\\subseteq N\\). Define \\(g(z)=z f(z)\\) on \\(\\overline{B}(0,r)\\setminus\\{0\\}\\). For such \\(z\\), the display above shows \\(|g(z)|\\le C r^{1/2}\\), so \\(g\\) is bounded and holomorphic on the punctured disc. By the removable-singularity theorem, \\(g\\) extends to a holomorphic \\(G\\) on \\(\\overline{B}(0,r)\\), and the inequality forces \\(G(0)=\\lim_{z\\to 0}g(z)=0\\).  \n\nNow consider the difference quotient \\(F(z) = (G(z)-G(0))/(z-0)\\) for \\(z\\neq 0\\) and \\(F(0)=G'(0)\\); in Mathlib this is the `dslope` of \\(G\\) at \\(0\\). The standard dslope lemma shows \\(F\\) is holomorphic on \\(B(0,r)\\). On \\(0<|z|<r\\) we have \\(G(z)=g(z)=z f(z)\\), so \\(F(z)=f(z)\\). Therefore \\(F\\) is a holomorphic extension of \\(f\\) across the puncture, proving that \\(0\\) is a removable singularity.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization (status).**  \n- Artifacts: `execute.md`, `proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, and `changelog.edn` under `/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98A06/apm-v2-a98A06-1775004274108/` now hold the reader-proof, term/strategy list, the Lean target `removableSingularity_halfPower`, and the Stage log.  \n- In Lean (`ApmCanaries/Frames/A98A06/Apm_v2_a98A06_1775004274108/Main.lean` & `Scratch.lean`) I set up the plan: encode the hypothesis on a small ball, define `g z = z * f z`, and aim to apply `Complex.differentiableOn_update_limUnder_of_bddAbove` followed by `Complex.differentiableOn_dslope`. Supporting lemmas (`bound_z_mul`, `extend_z_mul_f`) are drafted in `Scratch.lean`; the final `EqOn` glue is still being polished, so Stage‚ÄĮ3 remains ‚Äúin progress‚ÄĚ and I have not yet run `lake build`. No `sorry`s have been merged into `Main.lean`; once the dslope witness is wired up, the build/test step will follow.\n\n**What connects.**  The trick ‚Äúmultiply by \\(z\\) to gain boundedness, extend, then divide back‚ÄĚ is the baby version of the general principle behind Schwarz‚ÄďPick and higher-order Schwarz lemmas: if \\(f^{(k)}\\) is controlled and the first \\(k-1\\) derivatives vanish, then \\(f\\) obeys a \\(k\\)-th power bound. The same technique underlies proofs of the Casorati‚ÄďWeierstrass and Picard theorems (where we multiply by factors that kill apparent poles) and harmonic-measure estimates in PDE: whenever the data only bound a weighted norm, look for a simple factor that converts it into a genuine supremum bound before appealing to rigidity theorems.\n\n(See `execute.md` for the detailed stage notes and `changelog.edn` for logged progress; `proof-plan.edn` and `formal-alignment.edn` record the machine-readable plan and Lean target.)\n\n---\n\nUpdated `changelog.edn` so every entry‚ÄĒincluding the workspace-initialized record‚ÄĒnow carries the required `:full-record?`, `:sorry?`, and `:fully-closed?` fields. All other artifacts (`proof-plan.edn`, `